It's nicely rendered but the nerve felt too stylized for me to understand its course. It is hard to tell where the nerve is actually sitting spatially.

Great contrast/color. Great draftsmanship and craftsmanship. 

Objects have been simplified in an successful way. It's not overly detailed or unnecessarily 'scientific'. However, I am not sure if this is ideal for the intended audience.

The composition is okay--the speedometer is creating a tangent with the objects above, and it seems an unnecessary addition to show speed, which is already shown by the motion lines.

The composition is fair. 
The rendering on the virus particles is much more detailed than the rendering on anything else.

Unless there was a testifying witness who saw this UP CLOSE, it couldn’t be admitted under the general rules of admissible demonstrable evidence anywhere.  The purpose of a piece of demonstrable evidence or a demonstrable aid is to help the judge or jury better understand the testimony of an expert witness.  It must also not unfairly prejudice, inflame, confuse or mislead the jury. (text in red)
